# Rukn Course Studio — V1 Architecture Constraints

## No unnecessary dependencies/infra in V1

Do not introduce any of the following unless the user explicitly requests it in the conversation:

- LangChain (or similar LLM orchestration frameworks)
- Vector databases / embedding stores
- RAG frameworks
- Message queues (Celery, RabbitMQ, etc.)
- Redis
- Docker / containers
- Any cloud service (S3, cloud LLM hosting infra, managed DBs, etc.)

Prefer simple Python modules and explicit, readable orchestration code (plain
functions/classes, explicit control flow) over adding a framework to solve
orchestration. If a task seems to need one of the above, stop and ask the
user first instead of adding it.

## Strict frontend/backend ownership boundary

- The frontend (`frontend/`) is UI only. It never calls the AI provider
  directly and never contains generation logic.
- The backend (`backend/`) owns **all** generation logic: course map
  building, reel-by-reel generation, every review stage, and DOCX export.
- The frontend only talks to our own backend API — never directly to an LLM
  provider, embeddings API, or any other AI service.

## Never expose internal reel-by-reel generation to the user

- The multi-stage internal pipeline (map → reel-by-reel → per-reel review →
  every-5-reels review → per-module review → every-2-modules review →
  full-course review → export) is an internal implementation detail.
- API responses and UI must never surface individual reel drafts, review
  verdicts, or per-stage content as the product output.
- The user-facing result of a generation run is exactly one final DOCX, plus
  an optional short, coarse status string (e.g. `queued`, `generating`,
  `reviewing`, `exporting`, `done`, `failed`). Never a per-reel/per-module
  progress feed.

## Any big change must be broken down and explained first

Before implementing a change that touches multiple files, adds a new
module/service, or alters the pipeline/data model:

1. Explain the plan in plain language first (what files, why, in what order).
2. Break the implementation into small, single-purpose files/functions rather
   than one large file or one large diff.
3. Only proceed to write code after the plan has been stated.
